export const VOLUMES = {"I":{"title":"Jazz, smoke, brass, and cool blue","intro":"Jazz colour runs from the cool blue-and-cream of mid-century record sleeves to the smoke-and-brass warmth of the late-night club. The palette is sophisticated, warm-metal and cool-shadow, with one bright accent. Each refuses a flat 'old jazz sepia': the music's design language is bold blue, warm brass, and graphic contrast."},"II":{"title":"Punk, black, ransom-note, and shock","intro":"Punk's palette is confrontational — black leather and denim, the ransom-note collage of black-and-white photocopy, with one shock of pink, red, or yellow. The colour is DIY, high-contrast, and aggressive. Each refuses a tasteful muted scheme: punk is black, white, and a single screaming accent."},"III":{"title":"Disco, mirror-ball, gold, and glitter","intro":"Disco and funk colour is pure glamour — mirror-ball silver, glitter gold, hot pink and purple light, against a dark dancefloor. The palette is luminous, metallic, and saturated. Each refuses a muted retro-brown '70s look: disco is silver, gold, and saturated club light, not earth tones."},"IV":{"title":"Reggae, red-gold-green, smoke, and sun","intro":"Reggae and dub colour centres on the Rastafarian red, gold, and green, set against Kingston sun, dub-studio smoke, and the black of vinyl. The palette is warm, earthy, and symbolic. Each refuses a generic tropical brightness: this is specific Rasta tricolour and Jamaican-street warmth, not a beach postcard."},"V":{"title":"Hip-hop, concrete, gold, and spray-paint","intro":"Hip-hop colour spans the grey concrete and gold chains of golden-age New York, the spray-paint brights of graffiti, and the moody purples of Southern trap. The palette is urban, bold, and accent-gold. Each refuses a generic 'urban grey': hip-hop's visual language is vivid graffiti colour and gleaming gold against the concrete."},"VI":{"title":"Electronic music, acid, laser, and concrete","intro":"Electronic music colour runs from the acid-house smiley yellow to Detroit-techno chrome, Berlin-club concrete grey, and the full-spectrum lasers of a rave. The palette is synthetic, high-energy, and light-based. Each refuses a muted ambient palette: club electronic is saturated laser colour and acid brights against the dark."},"VII":{"title":"Metal, black, blood, and cold silver","intro":"Metal's palette is dark and dramatic — black leather and night, blood red, cold corpse-paint white and silver, and the deep green or blue of atmospheric subgenres. The colour is theatrical and high-contrast. Each refuses an all-black void: even metal uses one charged accent — blood red, frost blue, corpse white — against the dark."},"VIII":{"title":"Country & folk, denim, wheat, and rhinestone","intro":"Country and folk colour is warm Americana — denim blue, wheat and dust gold, weathered barn-wood, with the occasional flash of rhinestone-suit colour. The palette is earthy, nostalgic, and sun-worn. Each refuses a garish modern country-pop palette: this is denim, dust, and wood, with rhinestone as the one bright note."},"IX":{"title":"The concert hall, gilt, velvet, and candle","intro":"Classical and operatic colour is the grandeur of the hall — gilt and red velvet, the black-and-white of the orchestra, the warm wood of instruments, and candlelit baroque gold. The palette is rich, formal, and warm. Each refuses a cold austere palette: the concert hall is warm gilt, deep velvet, and instrument amber."},"X":{"title":"Psychedelia, liquid light and op-art","intro":"Psychedelic '60s colour is the liquid light-show and the concert poster — swirling complementary brights, op-art contrast, and the warm orange-and-pink of the Summer of Love. The palette is vibrant, swirling, and clashing-by-design. Each refuses a muted vintage wash: psychedelia is maximal saturated colour, deliberately vibrating."},"XI":{"title":"Idol pop, candy pastel and neon MV","intro":"K-pop and J-pop visual design is hyper-produced candy colour — pastel idol concepts, neon music-video sets, and Harajuku clash. The palette is bright, sweet, and saturated, switching between soft pastel and electric neon. Each refuses a muted indie palette: idol pop is deliberate candy brightness, pastel or neon, never understated."},"XII":{"title":"Blues & soul, juke-joint, Motown, and Stax","intro":"Blues and soul colour is warm and human — the smoky amber of a juke joint, the polished glamour of Motown, the earthy red-and-yellow of Stax, and the deep blue of the Delta night. The palette is warm, soulful, and grounded. Each refuses a cold modern grade: this is a warm world of amber light, gold suits, and deep blue, with one bright accent."}};
